    "body": "### Problem\n\n`_watch.lua`, and thus `autoread.lua`, does not handle the case where OS handles are exhausted. When using LSP this is not uncommon (on macOS at least: `(libuv) kqueue(): Too many open files`) with big projects.\n\n`vim._watch.watch()` silently drops `handle:start()` failures other than `ENOENT`. When the OS file-watcher capacity is exhausted (e.g. Linux `inotify` watch limit, `EMFILE`), callers receive a no-op `cancel` function and have no way to tell that the watcher is dead. Events never fire; functionality silently degrades.\n\nAffected callers:\n\n- watcher-driven `'autoread'` silently stops working (falls back to `FocusGained` / `:checktime`)\n- `lsp/_watchfiles.lua`: LSP `workspace/didChangeWatchedFiles` notifications stop arriving from the affected paths.\n- `M.active.watch` counter shows healthy values because we counted the cancel-handle, not whether `handle:start` succeeded.\n\n\nThe existing TODO in `_watch.lua` acknowledges the gap: https://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/37239e724e9362c11fcd6c4e0af73bf74ff1c295/runtime/lua/vim/_watch.lua#L130-L131\n\n## Repro\n\n\n```sh\n# Linux: lower inotify limit, then open many files in nvim\necho 8 | sudo tee /proc/sys/fs/inotify/max_user_watches\nnvim file1 file2 file3 ... file20  # past the limit, late buffers' watchers fail silently\n# externally modify any \"late\" file\n```\n\n## Proposal\n\n1. Return `(cancel, err)` from `M.watch` / `M.watchdirs`.\n2. TBD: what about `runtime/lua/vim/lsp/_watchfiles.lua` ?\n3. Bump a global `M.active.watch_failed` counter on `handle:start` failure.\n4. show advice in `:checkhealth`\n\n## Related\n\n- `:h inotify-limitations` (existing docs)\n- TODO at `runtime/lua/vim/_watch.lua:130`\n- https://github.com/neovim/neovim/pull/37971",
